7969:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****         /* RTOS ports that support interrupt nesting have the concept of a
7970:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * maximum  system call (or maximum API call) interrupt priority.
7971:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * Interrupts that are  above the maximum system call priority are keep
7972:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * permanently enabled, even when the RTOS kernel is in a critical section,
7973:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * but cannot make any calls to FreeRTOS API functions.  If configASSERT()
7974:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * is defined in FreeRTOSConfig.h then
7975:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * portASSERT_IF_INTERRUPT_PRIORITY_INVALID() will result in an assertion
7976:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * failure if a FreeRTOS API function is called from an interrupt that has
7977:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * been assigned a priority above the configured maximum system call
7978:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * priority.  Only FreeRTOS functions that end in FromISR can be called
7979:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * from interrupts  that have been assigned a priority at or (logically)
7980:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * below the maximum system call interrupt priority.  FreeRTOS maintains a
7981:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * separate interrupt safe API to ensure interrupt entry is as fast and as
7982:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * simple as possible.  More information (albeit Cortex-M specific) is
7983:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * provided on the following link:
7984:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/tasks.c ****          * https://www.FreeRTOS.org/RTOS-Cortex-M3-M4.html */
